ce:section.ce:para:
In order to illustrate the chiral origin of CCDs, the optical activity of multicolor CCDs is studied by circular dichroism spectra. Similar positive cotton effects at 201 nm, 249 nm and 273 nm could be clearly observed, indicating the obvious left-handed stereo structure of these CCDs (Fig. 1
                        i-l). By comparing with the circular dichroism information (200 nm and 215 nm) of chiral precursor (
                           Fig. S3
                        ), it is demonstrated that the inherent chiral chromophore in precursor (L-Pro) is reserved. Meanwhile, after the polymer carbonization reaction, some new chiral centers (signals at 249 nm and 273 nm) are produced for multicolor CCDs, corresponding to UV–vis absorption peaks in the region of 250–300 nm, which can be attributed to π–π* transitions of aromatic sp2 domains of CCDs in a chiral environment. Moreover, another novel circular dichroism signal outside the ultraviolet region is observed, which shifts from 468 nm to 490 nm along with the redshift of the fluorescence emission. Such signal may come from the n-π* transition of the surface groups on the carbon core. The above results indicate that L-Pro not only participates in the formation of carbon core but also provides chiral residues in the formed CCDs. According to present researches, it is well known that the carbon cores are progressively racemic under high temperature, CCDs are primarily composed of non-chiral carbon cores and chiral groups attached to the core surface [33–35]. Together with our previous work of chiral L/DGln-CDs prepared by L/D-Glutamine, the theoretical calculation results indicate that the newly emerged chiral signals in L/DGln-CDs are attributed to the stacking of adjacent carbonyl groups on the surface peptides of the CDs [36]. Therefore, we speculate that some chiral groups originated from the chiral L-Pro residues are attached to the core surface of multicolor CCDs, these chiral groups and the chiral environment they provided endow the CCD with chiral features. Unfortunately, no CPL signal is detected for these CCDs, which may be due to the limited combination of chiral center and chromophores in complex structures of CCDs (
                           Fig. S4
                        ).
